[White "Repertoire against Benko"]
[Black "INTRODUCTION"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A57"]
[Annotator "GM Evgeny Postny"]
[PlyCount "17"]

{The topic of current article is the Benko gambit (among russian speakers also
known as Volga gambit) that arises after the following opening moves:} 1. d4
Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 {This is the initial position. Black is sacrificing a
pawn as early as on move three! It is a clear indication that Black is very
ambitious, not playing for accurate equality, but ready to fight for an
initiative from the very beginning. The idea of sacrificing a pawn is to open
both "b" and "a" files for black's heavy pieces. Later after developing the
dark squared bishop to g7, Black is hoping to exert a serious pressure on
white's queenside.  In general White has two different approaches. One is to
accept the pawn sacrifice by 4.cxb5 and to try to defuse black's initiative in
the long term struggle. Second is to decline the pawn sacrifice, while
fighting for an initiative from the very beginning. In current article I will
present the example of the second approach.} 4. Qc2 {This is not the main
theoretical continuation, but it doesn't make it less ambitious! Usually, it
is not recommended to develop the queen at such an early stage. A dogmatic
rule say that you should develop knights and bishops at first. I must
emphasize that in most of the cases I recommend you to follow these rules.
However, by choosing Benko gambit Black creates a crisis on the board, which
requires special attention and concrete play. We can see that White seized
space in the center thanks to his pawn on d5 and it would be great if another
central pawn would join it. The move 4.Qc2 creates an idea of advancing the
"e" pawn to e4, which will cement white's control over the center.  This line
is not a frequent guest in top level tournaments. Nevertheless, two notable
grandmasters Shakhriyar Mamedyarov and Alexey Dreev has employed this line on
a regular basis, achieving good positions and good results as well.  Black has
numerous replies and we will examine them one after another, starting from
minor lines.} bxc4 ({Minor lines, such as} 4... b4) ({or} 4... Qa5+ {are
examined in chapter 1. White gets comfortable advantage.}) ({The move} 4... Na6
{(chapter 2) is also not exactly in the spirit of the position. White covers
the b4 square by} 5. a3 {and the knight remains misplaced on a6.}) (4... e6 {
takes us to chapter 3. White replies with} 5. e4 {and after} exd5 (5... bxc4 {
would transpose to chapters 5 and 6.}) 6. cxd5 {gets pleasant prospects.}) (
4... g6 5. e4 d6 {(black's fourth and fifth moves may also come in opposite
order) is examined in chapter 4. Black's desire to sacrifice a pawn is
objectively not recommended and White is better after} 6. cxb5) 5. e4 d6 (5...
e6 {is a serious alternative, undermining white's central pawns chain.} 6. Nc3
{is the most aggressive reply, examined in chapter 6.} (6. Bxc4 {is a solid
approach, examined in chapter 5.})) 6. Bxc4 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. h3 {
Useful prophylactic move. This position is examined in chapter 8. My
conclusion is that white's chances are slightly preferable.} ({If White
doesn't wish to spend a tempi on a pawn, then} 9. Nc3 {- see chapter 7.}) *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2016.10.24"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Benko gambit, 4.Qc2"]
[Black "Chapter 1: rare moves"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A57"]
[Annotator "GM Evgeny Postny"]
[PlyCount "37"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Qc2 b4 {This way Black releases the pressure on
the queenside and seizes some space. The white queenside knight can't be
developed now to c3. However, white's center is now stable and his space
superiority yields him better chances. Other alternatives I shall mention in
current game are: 4...Qa5 and 4...Bb7.} (4... Qa5+ 5. Nd2 $1 {The most
ambitious reply.} (5. Bd2 b4 6. e4 $14) 5... bxc4 6. e4 Na6 7. Bxc4 e6 $6 (7...
Nb4 8. Qb1 Ba6 9. Ngf3 e6 10. b3 $1 exd5 11. exd5 Bb7 ({The pawn can not be
taken:} 11... Nbxd5 $2 12. Bxd5 Nxd5 13. Qe4+ {wins a piece.[%cal Ge4e8,Ge4a8]}
) 12. O-O {followed by 13.Re1 with a powerful initiative for White.[%csl Re8]
[%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e8]}) 8. Ngf3 Nb4 9. Qc3 exd5 (9... Nxe4 $2 10. Nxe4 Nc2+ 11.
Kd2 Qxc3+ 12. Kxc3 Nxa1 13. Bf4 {The knight is trapped and the difference
between white's and black's pieces says it all about the position.[%csl Ra1]
[%cal Gh1a1]}) 10. exd5 Bd6 $2 (10... Qb6 {was necessary, but after} 11. O-O {
White is clearly better anyway.}) 11. O-O O-O 12. a3 Ba6 13. b3 {Now white's
rook is protected and Black has simply resigned as he is losing the whole
knight - 1-0 (13) Beliavsky,A (2650)-Bukal,V (2407) Nova Gorica 1999[%cal
Ga3b4]}) (4... Bb7 5. e4 bxc4 6. Bxc4 e6 7. Nc3 {The pawn on d5 is well
protected and the bishop on b7 remains passive.}) 5. e4 d6 6. a3 {This is a
key move for the position. By exchanging the b4-pawn, White not only
eliminates Black's space advantage on the queenside but at the same time he
brings his rook into play and frees the c3-square for the knight.} (6. f4 {is
an aggressive alternative.} g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Bd3 Bg4 $6 (8... O-O 9. O-O e6 {
would be a better plan for Black.}) 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. O-O a5 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Nxf3
$16 {1-0 (27) Mamedyarov,S (2753)-Caruana,F (2774) Moscow 2013}) 6... bxa3 (
6... Na6 7. Nf3 g6 $6 (7... e5 $14) 8. e5 $1 dxe5 9. Nxe5 {and the knight is
heading to c6.}) 7. Rxa3 {The reader should remember that this structure is
favorable for White. His d5-pawn gives him a considerable space advantage
while Black's a7-pawn is already a weakness.} g6 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. h3 {I don't see
any necessity in this move. The move 9...Bg4 is not a threat, therefore it was
preferable to develop a piece instead of a pawn move.} (9. Nf3 O-O 10. Be2 {
followed by castling would be the most natural. White's position is very
pleasant. He has space advantage and his pawn structure is superior. But, of
course, a whole fight would be still ahead.}) 9... O-O 10. Be2 Na6 11. Bg5 Qb6
12. Nf3 Rb8 13. Na4 Nb4 14. Qb1 Qc7 15. O-O e6 16. Re1 exd5 17. cxd5 Re8 18.
Nc3 Bd7 19. Nd2 {This position is very typical for Benoni defense. White's
advantage is out of question. Later on, he could put pressure on the d6-pawn
by means of Nc4 followed by Bf4. Moreover, we shouldn't forget that the weak
a7-pawn could be attacked either. On the other hand, Black has no serious
counterplay - the e4-pawn is protected, while the seemingly strong b4-knight
has no squares. In the forthcoming fight, however, White misplayed the
position and lost - 0-1 (42) Mamedyarov,S (2763)-Caruana,F (2709) Moscow 2010}
*

