[Annotator "GM Evgeny Postny"]
[PlyCount "33"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Qc2 Na6 5. a3 {Covering the b4 square and
asking a straight question: "What the knight is doing on a6?"} bxc4 (5... e6 6.
dxe6 fxe6 7. cxb5 Qa5+ 8. Bd2 Qxb5 9. e4 {is in white's favour. He will have
smooth development and the black king is not very safe in the long run.}) (5...
Qa5+ 6. Bd2 b4 7. e4 e5 8. dxe6 $2 {White gives away his space advantage for
no reason.} ({Simple development:} 8. Bd3 {followed by Ng1-e2 and castling
would secure white's small, but stable advantage.}) 8... dxe6 9. Nf3 Qc7 10.
Bd3 Bd6 11. O-O O-O $11 {0-1 (47) Andre,G (2262)-Hertneck,G (2461) Germany 2016
}) 6. e4 e6 7. Bxc4 {White goes for the positional appraoch. By protecting the
d5-pawn, he keeps his space advantage. Furthermore, in a long run, Black's
misplaced a6-knight will tell.} ({A more dynamic approach to the position
would have been} 7. dxe6 fxe6 8. e5 {Instead of taking the pawn back
immediately, White prefers to gain some space in the centre. Black has
problems to coordinate his forces.} ({It is interesting to point out that even
now the simple recapture} 8. Bxc4 {works well. For example, after} Qa5+ 9. Nc3
Nb4 10. Qb1 Nc6 11. Nf3 Ba6 12. b4 $1 cxb4 13. axb4 Qxb4 14. Bxa6 Qxc3+ 15. Bd2
Qc5 16. O-O $44 {White has more than sufficient compensation for the pawn. 1-0
(50) Ilincic,Z (2561)-Wang,P (2383) Budapest 2008}) 8... Nd5 9. Bxc4 Qa5+ 10.
Nc3 $1 {This is the most precise reaction.} ({After} 10. Bd2 $6 Nab4 11. Qb3
Ba6 12. Ra2 $1 {Black manages to save himself by a small trick:} Bxc4 13. Qxc4
Qa6 $1 14. Qxa6 Nxa6 $11) 10... Nab4 11. axb4 $1 Qxa1 12. Nxd5 exd5 13. Bxd5
Rb8 14. Ne2 {We reached a wild position, which looks dangerous for Black, as
his king is very unsafe.}) 7... exd5 8. exd5 Nc7 (8... Bd6 9. Nf3 O-O 10. O-O
h6 11. Nc3 $14 {0-1 (58) Juhasz,A (2185)-Szajbely,Z (2229) Budapest 2013}) 9.
Nc3 d6 ({In case of} 9... Bb7 {the pawn can be safely protected by} 10. Qd3 {
Black has no possibilities to increase pressure on the d5 pawn, meanwhile his
light pieces remain passive.}) 10. Nge2 {Remember this move! In this structure,
the knight is better placed on "e2" than on "f3". The f3-square is favorable
when White could put pressure on the d6-pawn by means of the manoeuvre
Nf3-d2-c4. In the concrete position, however, White should keep his bishop on
c4 since his central pawn needs protection ( in the normal Benoni structure,
White has pawn on e4 while Black has a pawn on b7). Moreover, in case of 10.
Nf3, Black could follow with 10...Bg4, intending to exchange the knight. Given
the fact that White has a space advantage, he should avoid the exchanges.} Be7
11. b4 {Very typical idea for this structure. White intends to provoke the
exchange 11...cxb4. In that case, he could occupy the weak c6-square by
playing Nd4-c6. If Black decides to refrain from taking on b4, White will go
for the exchange bxc5, creating a strong passed pawn in the centre.} O-O 12.
O-O Nd7 13. bxc5 dxc5 (13... Nxc5 14. Be3 Bf6 15. Rab1 {is also better for
White. As we have already pointed out, he could make use of the weakened
c6-square by playing Ne2-d4-c6.}) 14. Bf4 Nb6 15. Ba2 Ne8 16. Rfe1 Nd6 17. Ng3
$16 {White's advantage is out of question. He has more space better
coordinated pieces and a strong passed pawn. 1-0 (32) Mamedyarov,S (2731)
-Tregubov,P (2646) Ajaccio 2008} *

