[PlyCount "35"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Qc2 e6 5. e4 exd5 (5... bxc4 {transposes to
chapters 5 and 6.}) 6. cxd5 {Here we get a structure, similar to Benoni
defense. White has more space and control in the center, while Black is hoping
to get his play on the queenside.} ({After} 6. e5 $6 {Black has two options of
sacrificing a piece for a bunch of central pawns.} Ng4 (6... bxc4 7. exf6 Qxf6
8. Nc3 Bb7 $13) 7. Qe2 dxc4 8. Qxg4 d5 {In both cases the position is very
murky.}) (6. exd5 $6 {is also inaccurate, as here white's control over the
center is not so good as after 6.cxd5.}) 6... c4 $6 {Very ambitious, but risky.
} (6... a6 7. a4 {This is a very typical way to undermine Black's overextended
queenside. White's idea is to provoke the b5-b4 advance. Later on, he could
make use of the weakened c4-square by playing Nb1-d4-c4. Remember that c4 is
the perfect square for the knight in the Benoni structure. From there, the
knight puts pressure on d6 and blocks the queenside.} Qe7 8. Ne2 $1 (8. axb5 $2
Nxd5 $132 {[%cal Gd5b4]}) 8... Qxe4 9. Qxe4+ Nxe4 10. axb5 Bb7 11. Nec3 Nxc3
12. Nxc3 {Here it will not be easy for Black to develop his knight properly.
[%csl Yb8]}) ({More reasonable is the start attacking White's center
immediately} 6... Qe7 7. Bxb5 ({After} 7. Nc3 a6 8. Nf3 d6 (8... b4 $2 9. Na4
$16 {[%csl Ra8,Rc8][%cal Ga4b6]}) 9. Bd3 g6 {Black might eventually get a
decent version of Benoni setup.}) 7... Qxe4+ 8. Qxe4+ Nxe4 9. Ne2 {White is
definitely slightly better. The pawn on d5 is not a weakness, but hindering
black's smooth development.}) 7. Nc3 $1 ({In case of} 7. a4 $6 {Black can get
a counterplay by} Na6 $1 {targeting White's queen.[%cal Ga6b4]} 8. Nc3 (8. axb5
$2 {would run into} Nb4 9. Qxc4 Bb7 $17 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gc8c1,Gb4c2]}) 8... b4 9.
Nb5 b3 10. Qxc4 Bb7 {Black's advantage in development yields him a decent
compensation.[%cal Ga8c8,Gf8b4]}) 7... Bb4 ({After} 7... Qa5 $2 8. Bd2 Bc5 {
White should find the following sequence} 9. e5 Ng4 10. Qf5 $1 Nxf2 11. Ne4 Qb6
12. Nd6+ (12. Nxf2 $2 O-O {is not entirely clear.[%cal Gd7d6]}) 12... Bxd6 13.
exd6 O-O 14. Qxf2 {After eliminatng black's dangerous bishop it is far safer
to grab the knight. Black simply doesn't have enough compensation.}) 8. Be2 $6
(8. a4 {is very tempting, ruining Black's pawns chain on the queenside.} O-O 9.
axb5 Re8 10. Bxc4 Rxe4+ 11. Be2 Bb7 12. Nf3 {and after the following castling
White will be much better. Just look at these undeveloped black's queenside
pieces - rook on a8 and knight on b8!}) 8... O-O 9. Nf3 ({Again} 9. a4 {looks
more principled.}) 9... Re8 $6 (9... Qe7 $1 {was the right way to attack the
central pawn.} 10. e5 (10. Bg5 $2 {would be just a pawn blunder.} Qxe4 $17)
10... Nxd5 11. O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3 Bb7 13. Rd1 h6 {No doubt that White has good
compensation for the pawn, but here we can't say that Black got crushed in the
opening.}) 10. Bg5 h6 $6 (10... d6 11. O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3 Nbd7 13. a4 {is also
better for White.}) ({The pawn is, of course, taboo:} 10... Rxe4 $2 11. Bxf6
$18 {[%csl Re4]}) 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. O-O Bxc3 13. bxc3 Qg6 14. Nd4 Bb7 (14...
Qxe4 {would not make black's life any better.} 15. Qxe4 Rxe4 16. Rfe1 Na6 (
16... a6 $2 17. Nf5 $18 {[%cal Gf5d6]}) (16... Ba6 $2 17. Bf3 Rxe1+ 18. Rxe1
$18 {[%cal Ge1e8,Gd5d6]}) 17. Nxb5 $16 {[%cal Gb5d6]}) 15. Bf3 Na6 16. Rab1 Nc5
17. Rxb5 Rac8 18. Nf5 $16 {White is a clear pawn up and should win in the long
run, which he duly did - 1-0 (34) Nisipeanu,L (2678)-Tate,A (2292) Caleta 2011
CBM 141.} *

