[White "Benko gambit, 4.Qc2"]
[Black "Chapter 4: 4...g6; 4...d6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A57"]
[Annotator "GM Evgeny Postny"]
[PlyCount "35"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Qc2 g6 (4... d6 5. e4 g6 {would transpose to
our current game by different order of moves.} (5... bxc4 6. Bxc4 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7
8. O-O O-O {would lead us to chapters 7 and 8.})) 5. e4 d6 $6 (5... bxc4 {
would be the best choice for Black, transposing to the main line, which is
covered in chapters 7 and 8, as mentioned above.}) 6. cxb5 {If Black insists
to play a pawn down, White should eventually accept the challenge.} a6 (6...
Bg7 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Nf3 a6 {would change nothing and again leads to our game by
another order of moves. Black doesn't have too many ideas, so it's not
surprising that various orders of moves eventually lead to the same position.})
7. Nc3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. a4 axb5 (9... Bg4 10. Nd2 $16 {On the next move White
will play 11.h3, kicking away black's bishop, then develop the bishop to e2,
castle, probably establish the knight on c4 outpost and so on.}) 10. Bxb5 {
White managed to achieve a highly favorable version of Benko structure.
Usually, the construction a4+Bb5 prevents Black from creating counterplay on
the queenside. White's plan is fairly simple. After completing the development,
he could transfer his f3-knight to the perfect c4-square. Later on, White
could start preparing the central e4-e5 break.} Na6 {The knight is heading for
the weakened b4-square.[%cal Ga6b4]} 11. O-O Nb4 12. Qe2 {Generally speaking,
Black's b4-knight is never dangerous when it lacks support. Usually, White
manages to follow his plan by playing around that knight.} Ba6 (12... Bg4 {
yields Black a bit more chances for some compensation. Strangely enough, in
Benko gambit, despite being a pawn down, Black tries to provoke minor piece
exchanges. In this way, he eliminates White's space advantage and prevents him
from creating pressure in the centre and on the kingside.} 13. Bg5 {In the
Benko structure, White's dark-squared bishop is very well placed on the
g5-square. The reason is obvious. In order to open the way of his g7-bishop,
at some point, Black should remove his knight from f6. In that case, however,
his queen will be tied to the e7-pawn. Therefore, Black will experience
problems to connect his rooks.} Nd7 {The idea is to spoil White's kingside
structure after 14...Ne5.[%cal Gd7e5]} 14. h3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Nc2 16. Rab1 Nd4
17. Qd1 {White is still better, but here at least black's knight managed to
sneak into the central outpost.}) 13. Bg5 Ne8 {Black is planning to play 14...
Nc7 followed by an exchnage of the light-squared bishops. Later on, he could
start attacking the weak b5-pawn. Nevertheless, with his last move, he
restricts the mobility of the f8-rook. White finds an interesting way to
exploit it.} 14. Bxa6 Rxa6 15. Qd2 {Now, Black couldn't prevent the exchange
of his most important piece - the dark-squared bishop.[%cal Gg5h6]} Nc7 16. Bh6
{Exchanging the important bishop.} Bxh6 17. Qxh6 f6 18. Qd2 $16 {White is a
healthy pawn up and eventually brought home a full point in the game 1-0 (51)
Sumets,A (2633)-Kalegin,E (2461) LLucmajor 2014} *

