[Black "Chapter 5: 5.e4 e6 6.Bxc4"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A57"]
[Annotator "GM Evgeny Postny"]
[PlyCount "32"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Qc2 bxc4 5. e4 e6 6. Bxc4 ({A more aggressive
approach} 6. Nc3 {is covered in chapter 6.}) 6... exd5 7. exd5 d6 {This is a
standart pawn structure in this setup. Thanks to the advanced pawn on d5 White
has an advantage in space. However, it can also become a target. In future
Black might attack the pawn by Nb8-d7-b6 and Bc8-b7. White can support it by
Nb1-c3 and probably Ra1-d1.  I evaluate the position as marginally better for
White.} 8. Nc3 Be7 9. Nge2 {Developing the knight to e2, which later can go to
g3. Of course, it's also possible to put the knight on f3, but then White has
to take into account black's possibility Bg4.} (9. Nf3 O-O 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Bf4
({As White I would prefer to limit the opponent possibilities by prophylactic} 
11. h3 Nb6 12. b3 {and then to continue the development by Bc1-f4, etc.}) 11...
Nb6 12. b3 Bg4 13. Nd2 Bh5 14. Rfe1 Bg6 15. Qd1 Ne8 $6 {This is too passive.} (
{Instead, Black should strive for a more active counterplay by} 15... Nh5 16.
Be3 Bf6 ({Or even} 16... f5 $5)) 16. Qf3 Bf6 17. Rad1 Bxc3 18. Qxc3 $14 {1-0 
(40) Drozdovskij,Y (2552)-Kasparov,S (2491) playchess.com INT 2006}) 9... O-O
10. O-O Nbd7 11. Ng3 Nb6 12. b3 Ng4 {Quite a logical move. By making use of
the fact that White's knight is not on f3, Black goes for the manoeuvre Ng4-e5.
} ({Nevertheless, it was preferable to eliminate the bishop at first:} 12...
Nxc4 13. bxc4 {and only then to play} Ng4 {The position is approximately equal.
Nevertheless, White's space advantage gives him some chances to fight for an
edge.}) (12... Re8 13. Re1 Bf8 14. Bf4 Rxe1+ 15. Rxe1 Rb8 16. h3 Nxc4 17. bxc4
Qd7 $6 (17... Bd7 {was normal.}) 18. Nce4 Nxe4 19. Nxe4 $16 {This is a dream
position for White. He managed to keep his space advantage and develop all his
pieces harmoniously. The pawn on d6 is a long-term weakness. He went on to win
in the game 1-0 (34) Mamedyarov,S (2753)-Nguyen,N (2625) Khanty-Mansiysk 2013})
(12... Rb8 13. Re1 (13. h3 {This prophylactic move makes sense here as well,
covering the g4 square against the knight jump.}) 13... Nxc4 14. bxc4 Ng4 15.
Bf4 Bf6 16. h3 Nxf2 $5 {A speculative sacrifice, but interesting from
practical point of view. Black is hoping for a long term compensation.} ({A
safe option was} 16... Be5 17. Qd2 Bxf4 18. Qxf4 Ne5 $11) 17. Kxf2 Bd4+ 18. Be3
Qf6+ $2 (18... Be5 $1 19. Nge2 Qh4+ 20. g3 Qh5 $1 (20... Qxh3 $2 21. Rh1 {
would force Black to swap queens by[%csl Rh7][%cal Gc2h7,Gh1h7]} Qf5+ {which
is clearly in white's favour, considering that his king is unsafe.}) ({After} 
20... Qxc4 $6 21. Bf4 $1 Bxh3 22. Bxe5 dxe5 23. Qe4 {White achieves the
desirable queens exchange even at a price of some pawns.}) 21. Bf4 f6 {Black
has only one pawn for a piece, but his chances shall not be underesimated. The
h3 pawn is hanging, the bishop is coming to f5 and the open "b" file is also
at his disposal.}) 19. Kg1 Bxc3 20. Ne4 Bxa1 21. Nxf6+ Bxf6 {White's queen is
superior to black's rook + bishop + pawn and proved it in a few dozens of
moves in the game 1-0 (51) Sedlak,N (2575)-Vuckovic,B (2555) Mataruska Banja
2007}) 13. Bd3 $1 g6 14. h3 Ne5 15. Be2 $2 (15. Bh6 Re8 16. Bb5 $1 {A sudden
bishops attack from both flanks.} Bd7 17. f4 Bxb5 18. Nxb5 Ned7 19. Ne4 {with
a huge initiative for White.[%csl Rd6][%cal Gc2b2,Gf4f5]}) 15... f5 16. f4 Ned7
{Black has now a good position - ﾂ1/2-ﾂ1/2 (55) Erdos,V (2593)-Bologan,V (2693)
Caleta 2011} *

