1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Qc2 bxc4 5. e4 e6 6. Nc3 exd5 7. e5 {This is
White's most challenging option. Despite the fact that the arising positions
are extremely complicated, Black's play is much more difficult. That is why he
should know very well what he is doing.} (7. exd5 d6 8. Bxc4 {would transpose
to Chapter 5 (Game Erdos-Bologan).}) 7... Ng4 (7... Qe7 $2 {is met by the
symmetrical} 8. Qe2 {and Black is already in trouble. For instanse:} Ne4 ({
After} 8... d4 9. exf6 Qxe2+ 10. Ncxe2 {white's piece worth more than black's
pawns.}) (8... Ng8 9. Nxd5 {leads to a disaster for Black.}) 9. Nxd5 Qxe5 10.
Nc3 d5 11. f3 {wins a piece.}) (7... d4 $2 8. exf6 d5 (8... dxc3 $2 9. Qe4+ $18
) 9. Bxc4 $3 {This energetic blow refutes Black's 7...d4.} (9. Nxd5 $2 Qxd5 10.
Qxc4 Be6 11. Qxd5 Bxd5 {and White had to suffer in a worse endgame in the game
ﾂ1/2-ﾂ1/2 (30) Barria Zuniga,D (2438)-Pap,M (2496) San Sebastian 2011}) 9...
dxc4 (9... dxc3 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Qe2+ {winning.}) 10. Qe4+ Be6 11. Qxa8 dxc3
12. Ne2 {and White is simply an exchange up.}) ({An interesting piece
sacrifice was tried in one correspondence game:} 7... Bb7 $5 8. exf6 (8. Bg5
Be7 9. exf6 Bxf6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. O-O-O d4 12. Re1+ Kd8 {leads to a really
complicated position with chances for both sides.}) 8... Qxf6 9. Nf3 Na6 {
Black has a central pawn mass for the piece. Nevertheless, I believe that after
} 10. Bg5 {white's chances are slightly superior.}) 8. Nxd5 Bb7 $2 {This is
already a decisive mistake. The position is very sharp, so one mistake can
easily create an irreversible damage to the position. Good or bad, Black had
to grab the central pawn and hope for the best.} (8... Nxe5 9. Qe4 d6 10. Bf4 (
10. f4 f5 11. Qe3 Be6 12. Bxc4 Kf7 $1 13. fxe5 Qh4+ $13 {[%cal Gh4e1,Gh4c4]})
10... Nbc6 11. Nf3 Be6 12. Bxe5 dxe5 13. Bxc4 Bd6 14. Bb5 Bxd5 15. Bxc6+ Bxc6
16. Qxc6+ Ke7 17. O-O-O {with good compensation for the pawn.[%csl Re7][%cal
Gh1e1,Ge1e8,Gd1d8]}) 9. Bxc4 Nc6 ({After} 9... Nxe5 10. Qe2 Bd6 11. f4 O-O 12.
fxe5 Re8 13. Nf3 {White is simply a piece up.}) 10. Nf3 Be7 ({Again} 10...
Ngxe5 {loses a piece by the same way, as we saw before:} 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Qe2
Bd6 13. f4 $18) 11. Qf5 h5 12. O-O {White is already winning - 1-0 (74)
Mamedyarov,S (2719)-Bareev,E (2634) Moscow 2009} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2016.10.24"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Benko gambit, 4.Qc2"]
[Black "Chapter 7: 5.e4 d6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A57"]
[Annotator "GM Evgeny Postny"]
[PlyCount "27"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Qc2 bxc4 5. e4 d6 6. Bxc4 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. O-O
O-O 9. Nc3 (9. Re1 {was a choice of an expert of this line - Alexey Dreev.
However, Black got a decent position after} Nbd7 10. Nc3 Ng4 11. Bf1 Nde5 12.
Nxe5 Nxe5 13. Bg5 Rb8 $11 {1-0 (56) Dreev,A (2679)-Ivanisevic,I (2632) Jakarta
2013}) 9... Ba6 {We already know that in Benko type of structures, Black
always tries to get rid of his light-squared bishop. That is why his last move
is very logical.} (9... Nbd7 10. h3 {transposes to Chapter 8.}) ({The other
attempt to exchange the bishop} 9... Bg4 $6 {seems to be dubious since White
could simply remove the knight. The following sequence illustrates very well
the basic positional ideas in this structure.} 10. Nd2 Bc8 {Not an impressive
manoeuvre, but the bishop on g4 is really doing nothing.} 11. b3 {This is
another key move for the variation. White is planning to develop his bishop
via b2, thus challenging the g7-bishop.} Nbd7 12. Bb2 Nb6 13. Rfe1 {Very
instructive move. As we have already pointed out, White's knight belongs to
the c4-square. That is why White intends to continue 14.Bf1 followed by 15.Nc4.
Furthermore, from e1, the rook would support the typical e4-e5 advance.} Ne8
14. Bf1 e5 {Since Black is afraid of a possible exchange of the dark-squared
bishops, he goes for a KID type of structure. Now, he is planning to follow
with f7-f5. White, however, doesn't allow this plan to come true.} 15. dxe6
fxe6 16. Nb5 {It becomes clear that Black is not ready to play an open positon.
His forces are simply not coordinated.} Bxb2 17. Qxb2 Bd7 18. Rad1 {White
brings his last piece into play. White puts a considerable pressure on the
d6-pawn.} Qe7 19. Na3 $1 {with significant advantage for White. The pawn on d6
is a target and in general black's structure is somewhat loose. This occurred
in the game 1-0 (38) Dreev,A (2668)-Dubov,D (2624) Moscow 2013[%csl Rd6][%cal
Ga3c4,Gd1d6,Gd2c4]}) 10. Nb5 $1 {I like this move. The knight on b5 obstructs
black's play on the queenside. Meanwhile, to exchange it for a light-squared
bishop doesn't look too promising for Black as well.  The alternatives for
White are 10.Bxa6 and 10.Nd2. No problem with these moves, but I prefer the
move in the text.} Qb6 (10... Ne8 11. Bd2 {Important prophylactic move. White
prevents his opponent from playing 11...Nc7 since after this move, Black runs
into 12.Ba5. Another idea is to exchange the bishops via c3.} Nd7 (11... Nc7 $6
12. Ba5) 12. a4 Bxb5 13. axb5 {This move is also very important. White closes
the b-file and brings his rook into play. Taking with a pawn on b5 is quite a
typical decision for the Benko gambit.} Nb6 14. Be2 Nc7 15. Bc3 {Exchanging
black's most dangerous piece will secure white's small, but long-lasting
advantage thanks to space superiority.}) (10... Bxb5 {Even though Black
usually wants to get rid of his light-squared bishop, it is preferable to give
that bishop for the opponent's light-squared bishop or for the f3-knight. In
this position, White could establish a blockade on the light-squares by
transfering his knight to c4.} 11. Bxb5 Qb6 12. Be2 Nbd7 13. Nd2 (13. Rb1 Rab8
14. Rd1 $14) 13... Qc7 14. Rb1 {Moving the rook away from the x-ray of black's
dark-squared bishop is always useful.} a5 15. Bb5 (15. Nc4 $14) 15... a4 16.
Bxa4 Nb6 17. Bb3 Rfc8 18. Nc4 {Black has some compensation for the pawn, but,
I believe, it's not sufficient against precise play. This appeared in the game
ﾂ1/2-ﾂ1/2 (50) Moskalenko,V (2558)-Mihailovs,J (2408) Barbera del Valles 2009})
(10... Nbd7 $2 {would blunder a pawn after} 11. Nxd6 $1) 11. a4 Nbd7 12. h3 h6
$6 (12... Rfb8 {would be more to the point.} 13. Be3 (13. Bd2 {is also
possible. The bishop can also go to c3 to oppose the black counterpart on the
long diagonal.}) 13... Qb7 $14) 13. Be3 Ne8 14. Rab1 {White got a clear
advantage in the game 1-0 (35) Vojinovic,G (2474)-Ilic,D (2306) Dimitrovgrad
2003[%cal Gb2b4]} *

