[White "Benko gambit, 4.Qc2"]
[Black "Chapter 8: 9.h3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A57"]
[Annotator "GM Evgeny Postny"]
[PlyCount "31"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Qc2 bxc4 5. e4 d6 6. Bxc4 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. O-O
O-O 9. h3 {Here White makes a prophylactic move to cover the g4 square against
black's knight or bishop. Meanwhile, the knight is waiting on b1 and is
flexible to decide where to be developed according to the plan the opponent
will choose.} Ba6 {Since White couldn't avoid the exchange of the
light-squared bishops by playing 10.Nb5, Black tries his chance. Nevertheless,
White has another interesting resource.} ({A classical approach to the
position would be} 9... Nbd7 10. Nc3 Nb6 11. Be2 e6 {This is the most active
attempt for a counterplay for Black, but it also weakens the pawn on d6.} 12.
dxe6 Bxe6 13. Bg5 (13. Bf4 Qe7 14. Rad1 d5 15. exd5 Nfxd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 $11 {
1/2-1/2 (72) Goloshchapov,A (2586)-Kasimdzhanov,R (2700) Dubai 2014}) 13... h6
14. Bh4 $14 {Black can't push d6-d5 so easily and has to either make a
concession by g6-g5, or to suffer from inferior pawn structure.}) 10. Na3 $1 {
The most flexible way of development. Less precise is 10.Nbd2, which would
obstruct the dark squared bishop.} Nfd7 (10... Bxc4 11. Nxc4 Nbd7 12. Bg5 {Do
you remember this important move? By developing his bishop, White puts an
indirect pressure on the e7-pawn.} Nb6 13. Nfd2 {Of course! The powerful
c4-knight could be replaced only by another knight!} Nxc4 14. Nxc4 {White is
ready to start his central expansion. Later on, he could play Rad1, Rfe1
followed by f2-f4 and e4-e5. Black has problems to obtain a counterplay. 1-0 
(44) Krasenkow,M (2628)-Volodin,A (2506) Stockholm 2013}) 11. Rb1 {This
position was a matter of dispute between Mamedyarov and Jones in their rapid
match in Corsica. White was pressing in both games, but Black managed to hold.}
Bxc4 (11... Nb6 12. b3 Qc8 13. Bb2 Bxc4 14. Nxc4 Nxc4 15. bxc4 Bxb2 16. Qxb2
Nd7 17. e5 $14 {1/2-1/2 (44) Mamedyarov,S (2756)-Jones,G (2576) Bastia 2010})
12. Nxc4 Nb6 13. b3 ({Here I suggest a slight improvement for White:} 13. Ne3
$1 {keeping the knight away from the exchange, at least for a while. In
general, a side having space advantage (White in our case) should avoid
exchanges. This applies when pieces are equally active (passive). For example,
in such position an exchange of dark-squared bishops is recommended for White
as his bishop is more passive. Therefore, his plan for the next few moves
should include the manoeuvre Bc1-d2-c3, or b2-b3 followed by Bc1-b2.}) 13...
Nxc4 14. bxc4 {Also here White is minimally better thanks to space advantage.
On the other hand, black's position is out of weaknesses.} Nd7 15. Bg5 Re8 16.
Rb5 $14 {1/2-1/2 (41) Mamedyarov,S (2756)-Jones,G (2576) Bastia 2010} *

